  "text": "These hypotheses have led to the identification of other neurotrophic factors as putative antidepressant compounds. IGF-I is one such recent example. IGF-I administered centrally or peripherally increases adult hippocampal cell proliferation and neurogenesis, and also increases the differentiation of immature cells into neurons. [CITATION_1] To determine whether the neurotrophic fac-tor hypothesis would indeed yield a novel antidepressant-like compound, rats were administered IGF-I via intracerebroventricular administration. In agreement with the hypothesis, IGF-I produced an antidepressanteffect in the forced swim test, which lasted 6 days after infusion. [CITATION_2] Although the mechanism by which the IGF-I induced antidepressant activity occurs is unknown, this finding indicates that the search for drug targets by looking for the neurogenic potential of compounds may provide novel antidepressants.",
